	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p>No. 3719</p>
				<p rend="align(center)">OFFICE OF THE CHIEF RABBI.</p>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>London</placeName>&#44; <date>August 1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> 5622</date></p>
				<p>Revd &#38; Dear Sir&#47;</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">I have yet<lb/> to express my sincere thanks to<lb/> you for your very kind congratulations<lb/> on my son&#39;s promotion.  I hope<lb/> with his talents he will prove an<lb/> able &#38; zealous worker in the vine&#45;<lb/>yard of the Lord.  He has as yet&#44;<lb/> much to learn &#38; to study&#8212;but<lb/> at a later period I think he<lb/> will contribute to your paper.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Concerning your affairs with<lb/> your agent&#44; <persName>Mr John Joel</persName> I<lb/> have made accurate inquiries.<lb/>  He had been insured in the Alliance</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>Insurance office&#44; &#38; I have been<lb/> told on very good authority&#44; that he<lb/> has received from them the sum<lb/> of &#163;1200.  I have earnestly spoken<lb/> to him about your just claims&#8212;<lb/> he has answered me that he has<lb/> the sum of &#163;15&#45;3&#45;8 for you in<lb/> hand which he will hand to your<lb/> order.  Altho&#39; he was insured to<lb/> a large amount&#44; he says that<lb/> if he has liquidated his own debts<lb/> he shall have nothing left &#38; as<lb/> he had not received any orders<lb/> from you to injure his books<lb/> in <placeName>London</placeName> he thought that you<lb/> had probably insured them in <del><placeName>London</placeName></del><lb/> <placeName>America</placeName>.  Perhaps an<lb/> application to the Alliance Insurance</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>Office might be advisable&#44; to write<lb/> to <persName>Mr Maclagan</persName>&#44; the Secretary<lb/> <placeName>Bartholomew Lane</placeName>  ask whether your<lb/> books were specified among the stock<lb/> that was insured &#38; paid for.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I have since then received a communication from <persName>Mr<lb/> Samuel Solomon</persName>&#44; stating that he had<lb/> been appointed your agent.  He can<lb/> be of much service to recommend<lb/> the adoption of your Bible in the<lb/> Free School&#44; of which he is the <hi rend="underline">paid</hi><lb/> secretary.  I have spoken often<lb/> &#38; much in favour of your Bible&#59;<lb/> &#38; shall always continue to do so.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I have been told that the<lb/> Society for Diffusion of Religious<lb/> Knowledge are likely to take a thousand</p>
			<pb n="4"/>
				<p>copies of your Bible&#44; if you can give<lb/> them at 2&#47;3 each&#8212;bound I think it advisable<lb/> for you to enter into communication<lb/> upon the subject with <persName>N. S. Joseph<lb/> Esq.</persName> The Secretary&#44; East India<lb/> Chambers&#44; <placeName>Leadenbell St.</placeName></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I highly<lb/> appreciate your unremitting exertions<lb/> for the spiritual welfare of our<lb/> brethren in the &#39;land of trouble&#39;<lb/> <add>Hebrew</add></p>
			<p rend="indent(4)">I remain</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)">Revd &#38; Dear Sir&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)">Yours faithfully</p>
				<p><addressee>Revd Mr Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">&#38;c &#38;c &#38;c <persName role="author">N Adler Sr</persName></p>
		</body>
